( international ) research found learning barrier of premature infants can be overcome
xinhua news agency , washington , february 15 - underweight premature infants tend to have sluggish intelligence development and are more likely to experience learning barriers .
however , researcher at u.s. yale university recently found that this type of learning barrier could be overcome as the infants grew older .
studies have confirmed premature infants with a birth weight less than 1.5 kilograms are more likely to have complications in their neural system and more than 50 percent of these children require special assistance in school .
studies on animals in the past have suggested that there is a recovery after an injury to a developing brain . however , there has been no report this far about premature infants recovering from brain injuries .
according to media report here , yale researchers tracked and looked at 300 premature infants and tested their intelligence quotient ( iq ) at the age of 3 , 4-1 / 2 , 6 and 8 years old . the study found the learning capability of most children improved over time .
the study said about half of the premature infants classified as &quot; mentally handicapped &quot; at the age of 3 achieved an average score in vocabulary and iq tests after 5 years time .
however , about 23 percent of the infants , who suffered serious injury due to brain bleeding , showed little improvement in intelligence development .
researchers said family environment is the crucial factor affecting premature infants &apos; intelligence development .
children from a three-person family and those with mothers who had a higher level of education showed a higher iq scores .
